<subSubSection id="C31E01A5FF9BFFB5C9C0FE4FFB50B633" pageId="14" pageNumber="207" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8BBB522EFF9BFFB5C9C0FE4FFAD0B5AE" blockId="14.[136,1451,396,599]" pageId="14" pageNumber="207">
<emphasis id="B9708E3CFF9BFFB5C9C0FE4FFE68B5C2" bold="true" box="[136,470,396,422]" pageId="14" pageNumber="207">Distribution and habitat:—</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C0429ADFF9BFFB5C89EFE4FFD10B5C2" authorityName="Kunth" authorityYear="1817" box="[470,686,396,422]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Euphorbiaceae" genus="Euphorbia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malpighiales" pageId="14" pageNumber="207" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="serpens">
<emphasis id="B9708E3CFF9BFFB5C89EFE4FFD10B5C2" box="[470,686,396,422]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="207">Euphorbia serpens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a worldwide tropical and subtropical weed. In the State of 
<collectingRegion id="49C09CCCFF9BFFB5CCC9FE4FFF76B5AD" country="Brazil" name="Sao Paulo" pageId="14" pageNumber="207">São Paulo</collectingRegion>
the species is quite common (not as much so as 
<taxonomicName id="4C0429ADFF9BFFB5CBAFFE73FCD0B5AD" authorityName="Aiton" authorityYear="1789" box="[743,878,432,457]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Euphorbiaceae" genus="Euphorbia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malpighiales" pageId="14" pageNumber="207" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="prostrata">
<emphasis id="B9708E3CFF9BFFB5CBAFFE73FCD0B5AD" box="[743,878,432,457]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="207">E. prostrata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C0429ADFF9BFFB5CAECFE73FB8BB5AD" authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1753" box="[932,1077,431,457]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Euphorbiaceae" genus="Euphorbia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malpighiales" pageId="14" pageNumber="207" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="thymifolia">
<emphasis id="B9708E3CFF9BFFB5CAECFE73FB8BB5AD" box="[932,1077,431,457]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="207">E. thymifolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), mainly in disturbed areas.
</paragraph>
